<p>General information that is helpful on getting started with, producing and distributing Doom 3 engine mods.
</p>
<a name="What_is_a_mod.3F"></a><h2>What is a mod?</h2>
<p>Mods (short for modification) are made by the general public by building on and expanding the assets and mechanics of a existing game. They can include new items, weapons, characters, enemies, models, modes, textures, levels, and story lines. They also usually take place in unique locations. They can be single-player or multiplayer. Mods are generally seperated into two categories:
</p>
<dl><dt> Mods&nbsp;</dt><dd> These just modify the game mechanics of the source game and add little in terms of new content 
</dd><dt> Total conversions&nbsp;</dt><dd> These aim at totally replacing the assets and mechanics of the source to create an entirely new game
</dd></dl>
<a name="Getting_Started"></a><h2>Getting Started</h2>
<a name="Installing_the_Game"></a><h3>Installing the Game</h3>
<p>Before you start any editing you should first install the Doom 3 engine game of your choice into a directory with no spaces (with Doom 3, for example, the folder could be "d:\doom3" compared to "c:\program files\doom 3\). This avoids a few technical problems you would otherwise encounter. Also make sure to update it to the newest version available.
</p>
<a name="Base_and_Mod_Directories"></a><h3>Base and Mod Directories</h3>
<p><i>Add information about Base, Add-on Folder (fs_game_base) and Modfolder Directories</i>
</p>
<div><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Image:D3square_25.png" class="image" title="Image:D3square_25.png"><img src="/web/20070729231147im_/http://modwiki.net/w/images/2/23/D3square_25.png" alt="Image:D3square_25.png" width="25" height="25" longdesc="/wiki/Image:D3square_25.png" /></a> <b>Note:</b> Doom 3 only: <dl><dd><i>/base</i></dd></dl></div>
<div><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Image:D3square_25.png" class="image" title="Image:D3square_25.png"><img src="/web/20070729231147im_/http://modwiki.net/w/images/2/23/D3square_25.png" alt="Image:D3square_25.png" width="25" height="25" longdesc="/wiki/Image:D3square_25.png" /></a> <b>Note:</b> Doom 3: ROE only: <dl><dd><i>/d3xp (add-on folder)</i></dd></dl></div>
<div><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Image:Q4square_25.png" class="image" title="Image:Q4square_25.png"><img src="/web/20070729231147im_/http://modwiki.net/w/images/e/e8/Q4square_25.png" alt="Image:Q4square_25.png" width="25" height="25" longdesc="/wiki/Image:Q4square_25.png" /></a> <b>Note:</b> Quake 4 only: <dl><dd><i>/q4base</i></dd></dl></div>
<p>Although you can work in the game base directory it's strongly recommended that you create a new mod directory (eg "d:\doom3\mymod") to keep the game base folder clean of custom files and to not interfere with it's function. It should only contain the original <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/PK4_%28file_format%29" title="PK4 (file format)">.PK4</a> files and the directories created at runtime by the Doom 3 engine.
</p>
<a name="Starting_your_Mod"></a><h3>Starting your Mod</h3>
<p>To start your mod you could either start the source game and then use the "mods" selection in the main menu, if present. As you will often start your mod to test and play it is easier to create a simple shortcut. Simply add the following parameter to your command line:
</p>
<pre>d:\doom3\doom3.exe +set fs_game mymod 
</pre>
<p>This starts doom3 the game, with the mod folder set to "mymod". For further information on useful Doom 3 engine game start up parameters see here <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Startup_parameters" title="Startup parameters">Startup parameters</a>.
</p>
<div><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Image:D3square_25.png" class="image" title="Image:D3square_25.png"><img src="/web/20070729231147im_/http://modwiki.net/w/images/2/23/D3square_25.png" alt="Image:D3square_25.png" width="25" height="25" longdesc="/wiki/Image:D3square_25.png" /></a> <b>Note:</b> Doom 3: ROE only: <dl><dd><i>If you are modding for the Doom 3: Resurrection of Evil expansion then add "+set <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Fs_game_base_%28cvar%29" title="Fs game base (cvar)">fs_game_base</a> d3xp" to the shortcut</i></dd></dl></div>
<a name="Beginning_Editing"></a><h2>Beginning Editing</h2>
<a name="Analysing_Game_Assets"></a><h3>Analysing Game Assets</h3>
<p>A good start at understanding the Doom 3 engine is by looking at the content of the original game. To do this you need to unpack the  .<a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/PK4_%28file_format%29" title="PK4 (file format)">PK4</a> Files contained in the base game directory. It is best to extract them to a seperate folder (example: Doom3\basextract\) so they do not interfere with the regular performance of the game. Also note that you should expact them in alphabetic order, starting with the lowest number. 
</p><p>Looking at how the game and it's assets were built often helps understand many details of the engine. It is also helpful to check how something was done in the game if you're stuck with something. However beware that the unpacked assets of the game will weight multiple gigabytes. Make sure that you have enough free space or only extract parts.
</p>
<a name="Categories_of_Game_Design"></a><h3>Categories of Game Design</h3>
<p>See the following links for more information on the different aspects of modding and game design. Each of these links gives you an overview over the appropriate section as well as helpful links to tips and tools.
</p>
<dl><dt><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Coding" title="Coding">Coding</a>&nbsp;</dt><dd> Modification of the engine's source code
</dd><dt><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Mapping" title="Mapping">Mapping</a>&nbsp;</dt><dd> Information about level design and the tools
</dd><dt><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Modelling" title="Modelling">Modelling</a>&nbsp;</dt><dd> Modelling and file format information
</dd><dt><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Texturing" title="Texturing">Texturing</a>&nbsp;</dt><dd> Explanation of material shaders and image files
</dd><dt><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Scripting" title="Scripting">Scripting</a>&nbsp;</dt><dd> Information about Scripting for GUIs and Levels
</dd><dt><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Declarations" title="Declarations">Declarations</a>&nbsp;</dt><dd>  Declarations define the properties and behavior of game content
</dd></dl>
<a name="Distribution"></a><h2>Distribution</h2>
<p>Once you have finished your mod you will want to distribute it. This section will cover a few approaches to this. Also keep in mind that your means of distribution is usually the first thing the player sees of your game. Be sure to invest ample time into this as to not annoy the user with broken or overly complicated installs
</p>
<a name="Putting_it_all_Together"></a><h3>Putting it all Together</h3>
<a name="Creating_compressed_media_files"></a><h4>Creating compressed media files</h4>
<p>After you have all your assets done you will want to compress your media files so they take up less space. You can automatically generate a batch file to create compressed versions of .<a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/TGA_%28file_format%29" title="TGA (file format)">TGA</a> and .<a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/WAV_%28file_format%29" title="WAV (file format)">WAV</a> files. To do so you must complete the following:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Com_makingBuild_%28cvar%29" title="Com makingBuild (cvar)">com_makingBuild</a> 1
</li><li><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Image_useOfflineCompression_%28cvar%29" title="Image useOfflineCompression (cvar)">image_useOfflineCompression</a> 1
</li><li><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/StartBuild_%28console_command%29" title="StartBuild (console command)">startBuild</a>
</li><li><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Map_%28console_command%29" title="Map (console command)">map</a> &lt;mapname&gt;
</li><li><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/w/index.php?title=FinishBuild_%28console_command%29&amp;action=edit" class="new" title="FinishBuild (console command)">finishBuild</a>
</li></ul>
<p>You should now have two batch files present: <i>makedds.bat</i> and <i>makeogg.bat</i>. You must do this from your mod hierarchy as it will not work if you already put your assets into .PK4 files (see below).
</p>
<a name="Packing_your_assets"></a><h3>Packing your assets</h3>
<p>You should pack all your custom files into .<a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/PK4_%28file_format%29" title="PK4 (file format)">PK4</a> files. It is important that you have an intact folder hierarchy within your .PK4 files. As usual it helps to look at the original game assets if you have any questions. When you distribute your .PK4 file with your mod or map you should make sure that the root directory in the pak file only contains the following files:
</p>
<ul><li><i>addon.conf</i>  - See <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://zerowing.idsoftware.com/linux/doom/AddonPaks" class='external free' title="http://zerowing.idsoftware.com/linux/doom/AddonPaks">http://zerowing.idsoftware.com/linux/doom/AddonPaks</a>
</li><li><i>description.txt</i> - Optional text file for mod folder description (only needed for mods in seperate folders).
</li><li><i>binary.conf</i> - This <b>must</b> be included if the .PK4 contains compiled game code. Without the binary.conf the Doom 3 engine will not load your modified binaries.
</li><li><i>mod/mapname_readme.txt</i> - Your readme file, if you choose to add one. It's generally a bad idea to just call this readme.txt as anyone extracting the pack contents may overwrite an already existing readme.txt file.
</li></ul>
<div><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Image:D3square_25.png" class="image" title="Image:D3square_25.png"><img src="/web/20070729231147im_/http://modwiki.net/w/images/2/23/D3square_25.png" alt="Image:D3square_25.png" width="25" height="25" longdesc="/wiki/Image:D3square_25.png" /></a> <b>Note:</b> Doom 3 only: <dl><dd><i>Pre-1.3 versions of Doom 3 would copy your "doomkey" (and "xpkey" if you have the Doom 3: Resurrection of Evil expansion) file to all your mod folders. This means you have to be careful that you do NOT distribute this file along with your mod if you are still using these older versions of the game. Even if you upgraded to v1.3 you should make sure your mod folder does not have this file.</i></dd></dl></div>
